{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497042"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1463"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1463"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.42,0.05,0.09,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1463"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1463"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"3448"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3551"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49519"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of epigastric discomfort. These symptoms may occur at any time, often but not always after meals, and last for about an hour. He has no other symptoms. He has a 10 pack-year smoking history and drinks about two glasses of wine a day. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Apart from a BMI of 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in addition to lifestyle management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urea breath test","Empirical esomeprazole therapy","Helicobacter pylori serology","Upper endoscopy","Abdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms of dyspepsia without any red flag features. For patients under 60 years of age with dyspepsia and no alarm symptoms, the recommended approach is to test for \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E and treat if positive, followed by acid suppression therapy if symptoms persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it is a highly sensitive and specific non-invasive test for active \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection. If positive, eradication therapy would be initiated. It\u0027s important to perform this test before starting acid suppression therapy, as proton pump inhibitors can lead to false negative results. After completing the test a proton pump inhibitor could then be started if symptoms persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpirical esomeprazole therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the initial step because it would interfere with \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E testing. Proton pump inhibitors should be withheld for at least seven days before performing a urea breath test to avoid false negative results. While acid suppression is often effective for symptom relief in dyspepsia, testing for \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E should precede this treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E serology\u003C/strong\u003E is less preferred than the urea breath test because it cannot distinguish between current and past infections. Serology remains positive even after successful eradication and has a lower positive predictive value, particularly in low-prevalence populations. The urea breath test has a sensitivity of 95-97% and specificity of 95-96%, while serology has a sensitivity of 85-95% but specificity of only 79-90%. Stool antigen testing offers similar performance to the urea breath test with sensitivity and specificity both around 94-95%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the initial investigation for this patient who is under 60 years of age and has no alarm symptoms (such as weight loss, dysphagia, persistent vomiting, evidence of gastrointestinal bleeding, or family history of upper GI cancer). Endoscopy would be appropriate if the patient fails to respond to empirical treatment or if alarm symptoms develop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in the initial evaluation of uncomplicated dyspepsia. It would be more appropriate if there were concerns about biliary or pancreatic pathology, which is not suggested by this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to testing for \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E, lifestyle modifications are essential and should be emphasised, including weight reduction, smoking cessation, alcohol moderation, and dietary changes. These interventions can significantly improve dyspeptic symptoms regardless of \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori\u003C/em\u003E status.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients \u003C60 years of age with dyspepsia, non-invasive testing for Helicobacter pylori followed by treatment (if positive) is recommended as first-line management.","Proton pump inhibitors should be avoided before Helicobacter pylori testing in patients with dyspepsia as they can lead to false negative results.","Upper endoscopy is not first-line investigation for dyspepsia in patients \u003C60 years unless red flag symptoms are present."],"references":["Eusebi LH, Black CJ, Howden CW, et al. Effectiveness of management strategies for uninvestigated dyspepsia: systematic review and network meta-analysis. BMJ 2019; 367:l6483. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31826881/","Moayyedi PM, Lacy BE, Andrews CN, Enns RA, Howden CW, Vakil N. ACG and CAG Clinical Guideline: Management of Dyspepsia. Am J Gastroenterol. 2017;112(7):988\u20131013. doi:10.1038/ajg.2017.154. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/ajg/fulltext/2017/07000/acg_and_cag_clinical_guideline__management_of.10.aspx","Moayyedi PM, Lacy BE, Andrews CN. ACG and CAG Clinical Guideline: Management of  Dyspepsia. Am J Gastroenterol 2017; 112:988\u20131013."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1463"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-26T08:59:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-26T09:21:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG